paragraphs.text: %md # Oracle Machine Learning for R - Embedded R Execution ***Oracle Machine Learning for R*** (OML4R) makes the open source R scripting language and environment ready for the enterprise and big data. Designed for problems involving both large and small data volumes, OML4R integrates R with Oracle Autonomous Database, allowing users to run R commands and scripts for statistical, machine learning, and visualization analyses on database tables and views using R syntax. Many familiar R functions are overloaded that translate R behavior into SQL for running in-database, as well as new automatic machine learning capabilities. In this notebook, we highlight using OML4R embedded R execution. We first build a linear model in R directly, then create user-define R function to build the linear model, save the function to the script repository and then score data in parallel using R engines spawned by the Autonomous Database environment. We then show the invokation of these scripts using the SQL interface with embedded R execution. To use the SQL API for embedded R execution, a user-defined R function must reside in the OML4R script repository, and an Oracle Machine Learning (OML) cloud account `USERNAME`, `PASSWORD`, and `URL` must be provided to obtain an authentication token. msg.data:
Oracle Machine Learning for R - Embedded R Execution

Oracle Machine Learning for R (OML4R) makes the open source R scripting language and environment ready for the enterprise and big data. Designed for problems involving both large and small data volumes, OML4R integrates R with Oracle Autonomous Database, allowing users to run R commands and scripts for statistical, machine learning, and visualization analyses on database tables and views using R syntax. Many familiar R functions are overloaded that translate R behavior into SQL for running in-database, as well as new automatic machine learning capabilities.

In this notebook, we highlight using OML4R embedded R execution. We first build a linear model in R directly, then create user-define R function to build the linear model, save the function to the script repository and then score data in parallel using R engines spawned by the Autonomous Database environment. We then show the invokation of these scripts using the SQL interface with embedded R execution.

To use the SQL API for embedded R execution, a user-defined R function must reside in the OML4R script repository, and an Oracle Machine Learning (OML) cloud account USERNAME, PASSWORD, and URL must be provided to obtain an authentication token.

Copyright (c) 2022 Oracle Corporation

The Universal Permissive License (UPL), Version 1.0

## Import libraries supporting OML4R and create a data table

To use OML4R, first load the ***ORE*** library.

Users can get online help using R's help function and specifying the function of interest.

msg.data:
Import libraries supporting OML4R and create a data table

To use OML4R, first load the ORE library.

Users can get online help using R's help function and specifying the function of interest.

paragraphs.title: Import R libraries
paragraphs.text:
%r

library(ORE)
library(lattice)

options(ore.warn.order=FALSE)

paragraphs.title: Get a proxy object for the IRIS_R table
paragraphs.text:
%r

ore.sync(table = 'IRIS_R')
IRIS <- IRIS_R
head(IRIS)

paragraphs.text:
%md

# Build and score a linear model directly in R

A best practice with embedded R execution is to validate your R script, and then your user-defined function before invoking the embedded R APIs. The next few paragraphs exercise the functionality we want.

We will create a linear model and pull the data to our local environment to invoke the base R linear model function.

msg.data:
Build and score a linear model directly in R

A best practice with embedded R execution is to validate your R script, and then your user-defined function before invoking the embedded R APIs. The next few paragraphs exercise the functionality we want.

We will create a linear model and pull the data to our local environment to invoke the base R linear model function.

paragraphs.text:
%r

iris_df <- ore.pull(IRIS)

lm_mod <- lm(Petal.Length~Petal.Width, iris_df)

%r

prediction <- predict(lm_mod,iris_df)
RES_DF <- cbind(prediction,iris_df)

z.show(head(RES_DF))

paragraphs.text:
%r

x <- ore.pull(RES_DF[['Petal.Width']])
y <- ore.pull(RES_DF[['Petal.Length']])

xyplot(y~x, xlab = "Petal Width", ylab = "Petal Length", 
  panel = function(x,y) {
  panel.dotplot(x,y)
  panel.abline(lm(y ~ x))
  }, 
  xlim=c(0,2.7), 
  ylim=c(0,7.5),
  main="Prediction of Petal Length")

paragraphs.text:
%md

# Build this same model using embedded R execution

Using embedded R execution, let's build the same linear model, but with spawned R engines under control of the Autonomous Database environment. First, we'll define our function, ***buildLM.1***, that returns the model as the result. We refer to this as a "user-defined function." As we did above, we'll go further and score the training data and plot the model against the data points. Note that embedded R execution can return images as well as structured content in the R API. In the SQL API, as you'll see in another script, you choose between structured data, images, or XML output.

We run this function to ensure it returns what we expect. In this case, both an image and a model.

msg.data:
Build this same model using embedded R execution

Using embedded R execution, let's build the same linear model, but with spawned R engines under control of the Autonomous Database environment. First, we'll define our function, buildLM.1, that returns the model as the result. We refer to this as a “user-defined function.” As we did above, we'll go further and score the training data and plot the model against the data points. Note that embedded R execution can return images as well as structured content in the R API. In the SQL API, as you'll see in another script, you choose between structured data, images, or XML output.

We run this function to ensure it returns what we expect. In this case, both an image and a model.

paragraphs.text:
%r

buildLM.1(iris_df)

paragraphs.text:
%md

________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
The ***tableApply*** function takes the proxy object *IRIS* as input data and loads that data to the user-defined function as a data frame. The user-defined function is passed as a string. We see that the model comes back as an OML object and see that it's the linear model.

msg.data: The tableApply function takes the proxy object IRIS as input data and loads that data to the user-defined function as a data frame. The user-defined function is passed as a string. We see that the model comes back as an OML object and see that it's the linear model.

paragraphs.text:
%r

mod <- ore.tableApply(IRIS, 
                      buildLM.1, 
                      dsname = 'ds-00')

cat("Type :",class(mod))
cat("\n")
cat("Coefficient :",(mod$coefficient))

msg.data:
Type : lm
Coefficient : 1.083558 2.22994

paragraphs.text:
%md

We can now save this user-defined function in the script repository and invoke this function by providing the function name.

msg.data: We can now save this user-defined function in the script repository and invoke this function by providing the function name.

paragraphs.text:
%r

ore.scriptCreate(name = 'buildLM.1', 
                 FUN  = buildLM.1,     
                 overwrite = TRUE)
                 
ore.scriptList(name = "buildLM.1")

A data.frame: 1 x 2
NAMESCRIPT
<chr><chr>
buildLM.1function (dat, dsname) { library(lattice) regr <- lm(Petal.Length ~ Petal.Width, dat) x <- dat[["Petal.Width"]] y <- dat[["Petal.Length"]] xyplot(y ~ x, xlab = "Petal Width", ylab = "Petal Length", panel = function(x, y) { panel.dotplot(x, y) panel.abline(lm(y ~ x)) }, xlim = c(0, 2.7), ylim = c(0, 7.5), main = "Prediction of Petal Length") return(regr) }

paragraphs.text:
%md

Notice the value to ***func*** is now a string, not a R function object, however, the results are the same. That's because we are now referencing the script in the script repository. We will save the model outputted by the tableApply to the datastore ds-0.

msg.data: Notice the value to func is now a string, not a R function object, however, the results are the same. That's because we are now referencing the script in the script repository. We will save the model outputted by the tableApply to the datastore ds-0.

paragraphs.text:
%r

mod <- ore.tableApply(IRIS, 
                      FUN.NAME = 'buildLM.1', 
                      dsname = 'ds-0')

cat("Type :",class(mod))
cat("\n")
cat("Coefficient :",(mod$coefficient))

ore.save(mod, name="ds1", overwrite = TRUE)

msg.data:
Type : lm
Coefficient : 1.083558 2.22994

paragraphs.text:
%md

______________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
The ***ore.rowApply*** function can be used to invoke a user-defined function on chunks of rows, which is useful to perform scoring in parallel for native R models. In this example, the user-defined function ***scoreLM.1*** takes a data frame and a model name. The ***ore.rowApply*** invocation takes as arguments the proxy object *IRIS*, that we want 10 rows scored at a time (resulting in 15 function invocations), the user-defined functions, the linear model object, and that we want the result to be returned as a single table.

For illustrative purposes, you can also use the ***ore.groupApply*** function to partition the data according to one or more columns and score as well, passing the model as an argument, and invoke the model on each partition.

The ore.rowApply function can be used to invoke a user-defined function on chunks of rows, which is useful to perform scoring in parallel for native R models. In this example, the user-defined function scoreLM.1 takes a data frame and a model name. The ore.rowApply invocation takes as arguments the proxy object IRIS, that we want 10 rows scored at a time (resulting in 15 function invocations), the user-defined functions, the linear model object, and that we want the result to be returned as a single table.

For illustrative purposes, you can also use the ore.groupApply function to partition the data according to one or more columns and score as well, passing the model as an argument, and invoke the model on each partition.

# Build one model per SPECIES using Group Apply

A better use of ***groupApply*** - the ability to automatically split the table data based on values in one or more columns - is for model building. The user-defined function can be invoked on each group. The function ***groupApply*** makes this easy, as well as specifying the desired number of parallel R engines using the ***parallel*** argument.

Here, we build three models, one specific to each species, and return them.

The ***ore.indexApply*** function allows the same function to invoked a specified number of times. The first argument to the user-defined function is an index number for the function execution. For example, if the "times" argument is 12, each function invocation will receive a distinct value between 1 and 10. This can be used, e.g., for selecting behavior within the function or setting a random seed for Monte Carlo analysis.

paragraphs.text:
%md

# Use the SQL API for embedded R execution

On Autonomous Database, OML4R provides a SQL interfaces for setting authorization tokens, and running UDFs to database tables directly from SQL. Supporting OML4R embedded R execution is the ability to load and store UDFs in the database script repository and R objects in the database datastore as displayed previously in the notebook. The datastore also enables loading saved objects for use in UDFs. Since it’s under database control and invoked through SQL, deploying R-based solution in production systems is greatly simplified. Further, scheduling R functions to run is easily achieved using DBMS_SCHEDULER or other scheduling interfaces that invoke SQL.

The service levels  `LOW`, `MEDIUM`, and `HIGH` provide different levels of performance and concurrency for an Autonomous Database instance. In this case, we use service level `MEDIUM` to enable moderate parallelism.

The `OUT_FMT` parameter controls the format of output returned by the embedded R execution functions.

The supported output formats are:

- JSON
- Relational
- XML
- PNG
- Asynchronous Mode Output

To use the SQL API for embedded R execution, a UDF must reside in the OML4R script repository, and an Oracle Machine Learning (OML) cloud account `USERNAME` `PASSWORD` and `URL` must be provided for an authentication token.

### **SQL API Workflow**

In the coming steps, we will provide a typical workflow for using the OML4R SQL API for embedded R execution with Oracle Autonomous Database:

- Connect to Autonomous Database as the ADMIN user and add the OML user to cloud host ACL list
- Confirm the host ACL list contains an entry for the OML user
- Obtain an authorization token to access the SQL API
- Confirm the token is set
- Invoke UDFs using embedded R execution from the OML4R R and SQL APIs

paragraphs.title: Obtain an authorization token
paragraphs.text:
%md

The OML4R SQL API uses tokens to authenticate an OML user. To authenticate and obtain an access token, use `cURL` or another REST client, such as Postman, to exchange the OML user credentials for an authorization token. Send a POST request to the token URL endpoint */oauth2/v1/token* with your OML username and password. The token URL can be obtained from the OML service console in Autonomous Database:

- Sign into your Oracle Cloud Infrastructure account. You will need your OCI user name and password.
- Click the hamburger menu and select the provisioned Autonomous Database instance. 
- Click **Service Console** and then click **Development**.
- Scroll down to **Oracle Machine Learning RESTful Services** tile and click Copy to obtain the following URLs for:
- Obtaining the REST authentication token for REST APIs provided by OML:

    *oml-cloud-service-location-url*/omlusers/

The URL *oml-cloud-service-location-url* includes the tenancy ID, location, and database name. For example, https://qtraya2braestch-omldb.adb.us-sanjose-1.oraclecloudapps.com.

For example,

- qtraya2braestch is the tenancy ID
- omldb is the database name
- us-sanjose-1 is the datacenter region
- oraclecloudapps.com is the root domain

paragraphs.title: Run the same function using the SQL API table function rqTableEval
paragraphs.text:
%md

Invoke the `buildLM.2` UDF that was created in R with the SQL API by running a SELECT statement that uses `rqTableEval`. 

The `rqTableEval` function runs a user-defined R function on data from an Oracle Database table.

The `inp_nam` parameter of `rqTableEval` specifies the IRIS table as the data to pass to the UDF. The `par_lst` parameter specifies the names of the model and datastore to pass to the UDF. The `out_fmt` parameter specifies returning the value as an XML string and the `scr_name` parameter specifies the script name `buildLM.2` UDF in the script repository to invoke. For this invocation, we persist the model to a new datastore, `ds2`.

msg.data:
Invoke the buildLM.2 UDF that was created in R with the SQL API by running a SELECT statement that uses rqTableEval.

The rqTableEval function runs a user-defined R function on data from an Oracle Database table.

The inp_nam parameter of rqTableEval specifies the IRIS table as the data to pass to the UDF. The par_lst parameter specifies the names of the model and datastore to pass to the UDF. The out_fmt parameter specifies returning the value as an XML string and the scr_name parameter specifies the script name buildLM.2 UDF in the script repository to invoke. For this invocation, we persist the model to a new datastore, ds2.

paragraphs.text:
%script

SET LONG 5000
    
SELECT *  FROM table(rqTableEval(
        inp_nam  => 'IRIS_R',
        par_lst  => '{"dsname":"ds2", "ore_parallel_flag":true, "ore_service_level":"MEDIUM"}',
        out_fmt  => 'XML',
        scr_name => 'buildLM.2'));

paragraphs.text:
%md

The `rqRowEval` function chunks data into sets of rows and then runs a user-defined R function on each chunk.

The `rRowEval` function passes the data specified by the `inp_nam` parameter to the R function specified by the `scr_name` parameter. You can pass arguments to the R function with the `par_lst` parameter.

The `row_num` parameter specifies the maximum number of rows to pass to each invocation of the R function. The last set of rows may have fewer rows than the number specified.

msg.data:
The rqRowEval function chunks data into sets of rows and then runs a user-defined R function on each chunk.

The rRowEval function passes the data specified by the inp_nam parameter to the R function specified by the scr_name parameter. You can pass arguments to the R function with the par_lst parameter.

The row_num parameter specifies the maximum number of rows to pass to each invocation of the R function. The last set of rows may have fewer rows than the number specified.

paragraphs.title: Run the same function using the SQL API table function rqRowEval with structured table output
paragraphs.text:
%sql

SELECT *  FROM table(rqRowEval(
        inp_nam  => 'IRIS_R',
        par_lst  => '{"dsname":"ds2", "ore_parallel_flag":true, "ore_service_level":"MEDIUM"}',
        out_fmt  => '{"Petal.Length_prediction":"number", "Petal.Length":"number", "Species":"varchar2(20)"}',
        row_num  => 50,
        scr_name => 'scoreLM.1'));

paragraphs.text:
%md

---
Invoke the `buildLM.group` function that's stored in the script repository from the SQL API. As in we did in the R API, group data by the `Species` column and set the `ore_parallel_flag` to true to leverage multiple R engines in parallel. Specify the Autonomous Database service level to use with the optional `ore_service_level` argument. The service names are `LOW`, `MEDIUM`, and `HIGH`. The service names provide different levels of performance and concurrency for an Autonomous Database. In this case, we use service level `MEDIUM` to enable moderate parallelism.

The service names provide different levels of performance and concurrency for an Autonomous Database. In this case, we use service level MEDIUM to enable moderate parallelism.

            inp_nam  => 'IRIS_R',
            par_lst  => '{"ore_parallel_flag":true, "ore_service_level":"MEDIUM"}',
            out_fmt  => 'XML',
            grp_col  => 'Species',
            scr_name => 'buildLM.group'));

Here, we create a function ***RandomRedDots*** that creates a simple data frame and generates two plots of random red dots. We create a function in the R Script Repository named "RandomRedDots", and then run the native R function.

msg.data:
Multiple images returned from embedded R execution

Here, we create a function RandomRedDots that creates a simple data frame and generates two plots of random red dots. We create a function in the R Script Repository named “RandomRedDots”, and then run the native R function.

paragraphs.text:
%r

RandomRedDots <- function(num_dots_1 = 100, num_dots_2=10){

    library(lattice)
    x <- sample(num_dots_1)
    y <- sample(num_dots_1)

    print(xyplot(y~x,
      main="Random Red Dots",
      pch = 19,
      col = "red"))
    
    x1 <- sample(num_dots_2)
    y1 <- sample(num_dots_2) 
      
    print(xyplot(y1~x1,
      pch = 19,
      col = "red",
      main="Random Red Dots"))
      
}


ore.scriptCreate(name = 'RandomRedDots', 
                 FUN  =  RandomRedDots,     
                 overwrite = TRUE)

%r

RandomRedDots()

%md

Invoke the *RandomRedDots* function from the REST API with *graphicsFlag* to *true*:

msg.data: Invoke the RandomRedDots function from the REST API with graphicsFlag to true:

paragraphs.text:
---
---

$ curl -X POST --header "Authorization: Bearer ${token}" --header 'Content-Type: application/json' --header 'Accept: application/json' -d '{"graphicsFlag":true}' "${omlserver}/oml/api/r-scripts/v1/do-eval/RandomRedDots"

%md

Here, we create separate figure objects and then create the scatter plot. We'll store this in the script repository as "RandomRedDots2" and 
invoke the function to see the results. As expected, we get both plots.

Now, when we invoke "RandomRedDots2" using embedded R execution, we get both plots shown in the result.

msg.data:
Here, we create separate figure objects and then create the scatter plot. We'll store this in the script repository as “RandomRedDots2” and
invoke the function to see the results. As expected, we get both plots.

Now, when we invoke “RandomRedDots2” using embedded R execution, we get both plots shown in the result.

paragraphs.text:
%r

RandomRedDots.2 <- function(num_dots_1 = 100, num_dots_2=10){

    library(lattice)
    x <- sample(num_dots_1)
    y <- sample(num_dots_1)

    fig1 <- xyplot(y~x, 
      pch = 19,
      col = "red", 
      main="Random Red Dots")
      
    print(fig1)
    
    x1 <- sample(num_dots_2)
    y1 <- sample(num_dots_2) 
      
    fig2 <- xyplot(y1~x1,
      pch = 19,
      col = "red",
      main="Random Red Dots")
      
    print(fig2)

}

ore.scriptCreate(name = 'RandomRedDots.2', 
                 FUN  =  RandomRedDots.2,     
                 overwrite = TRUE)

Another way to approach this is to create a single plot composed to two subplots. This approach is somewhat simpler, but yields only a single image. Generating two images may be desired when using the SQL API so that each image is returned as a separate row. See the SQL API demo script for an example.

msg.data: Another way to approach this is to create a single plot composed to two subplots. This approach is somewhat simpler, but yields only a single image. Generating two images may be desired when using the SQL API so that each image is returned as a separate row. See the SQL API demo script for an example.

paragraphs.text:
%r

RandomRedDots.3 <- function(num_dots_1 = 100, num_dots_2=10){

    library(lattice)
    fig1 <- xyplot(sample(num_dots_1)~sample(num_dots_1), 
      pch = 19,
      col = "red", 
      main="Random Red Dots")
      
    fig2 <- xyplot(sample(num_dots_2)~sample(num_dots_2),
      pch = 19,
      col = "red", 
      main="Random Red Dots")
      
      print(fig1)
      print(fig2)
}

ore.scriptCreate(name = 'RandomRedDots.3', 
                 FUN  =  RandomRedDots.3,     
                 overwrite = TRUE)
                 
ore.doEval(FUN.NAME = 'RandomRedDots.3')

function (num_dots_1 = 100, num_dots_2 = 10) 
{
    library(lattice)
    fig1 <- xyplot(sample(num_dots_1) ~ sample(num_dots_1), pch = 19, 
        col = "red", main = "Random Red Dots")
    fig2 <- xyplot(sample(num_dots_2) ~ sample(num_dots_2), pch = 19, 
        col = "red", main = "Random Red Dots")
    print(fig1)
    print(fig2)
}
